            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 15,
            AppRoutes = """["/admin/connections"]""",
            Tags = """["admin","integrations","connections","security"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Connections Registry\n\nNavigate to **Admin → Connections** for a single, read-only roll-up of every credential and connection your install has issued or accepted. It does not create or change anything — it is an audit view that answers \"what is connected, who owns it, and is it healthy?\" in one place. Any actual operation (issue, revoke, reconnect) is done on the connection's own native admin page, reached via the **Manage** button on its row.\n\n### What Shows Up Here\n\nThe registry federates several credential sources into one table:\n\n- **BI API Key** — reporting keys used by business-intelligence tools (see the API Keys module)\n- **System API Key** — keys for software that signs in as a user\n- **EDI Trading Partner** — X12/EDIFACT partner connections\n- **QuickBooks** — the accounting-provider connection\n- **Communication Sync** — email and messaging sync links\n- **Cloud Storage Link** — outside file-storage connections\n\n### Reading a Row\n\nEach row shows:\n\n- **Kind** — an icon + label for the connection type above\n- **Name** — the human label for that specific connection\n- **Owner** — the user's email for user-scoped credentials, or **Install-level** when the connection belongs to the whole install rather than one person\n- **Status** — the native source's own word for health (see below)\n- **Last Used** / **Created** — dates; Last Used reads **Never** when the credential has not been used yet\n\n### Status Vocabulary\n\nEach source uses its own status words, which the registry color-codes onto a shared chip palette:\n\n- **Green (healthy):** Active, Connected, Linked\n- **Amber (attention):** Expired\n- **Neutral (inactive):** Revoked, Disconnected, Inactive\n\nA green chip means the connection is live; amber means it needs renewal soon; neutral means it is turned off or was revoked.\n\n### The Manage Button\n\nThe registry never changes anything itself. To act on a connection, click **Manage** on its row — it takes you straight to that connection's own admin page (for example, a System API Key row sends you to **Admin → System API Keys**, a QuickBooks row to **Admin → Integrations**, an EDI partner to **Admin → EDI**). Do the issue, revoke, or reconnect work there, then return to the registry to confirm the new status.\n\n### Who Can See It\n\nThe Connections registry is **Admin-only**, and it is controlled by the same setting that governs API keys. Because the list reveals which credentials exist, who owns them, and when each was last used, it is treated as sensitive even though no secret is ever shown in full. If that setting is turned off for your install, a banner explains why and the table stays empty.","sections":[]}"""
