            Tags = """["admin","api-keys","integrations","security"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## API Keys for Integrations and BI\n\nForge can hand out long-lived keys so software — not a person at a browser — can call its API. There are two kinds, on two admin tabs:\n\n- **System API Keys** (**Admin → System API Keys**) — for integrations that run on their own and act *as* a real user (a nightly sync script, a connector to another system).\n- **BI API Keys** (**Admin → BI API Keys**) — for reporting and business-intelligence tools (Power BI, Metabase) pulling data out.\n\nBoth tabs are **Admin-only**, controlled by an API-keys setting for your install. If that setting is off, the New Key button is disabled and a banner explains why.\n\n### Issuing a Key\n\nClick **New Key**. Give it a clear **Name** (you'll recognize it later in the list — \"Power BI nightly pull\", not \"key 3\"). Then:\n\n- **User** — every key is **bound to a real user**. The key authenticates *as* that person and inherits their permissions. Pick a user whose access matches what the integration legitimately needs; don't bind a reporting tool to a full admin.\n- **Role Template** (optional) — narrow the key's effective roles to a rollup template instead of the user's full role set. This is how you give a key *less* than its owning user has.\n- **Expires At** (optional) — set an expiry date for keys that should auto-retire; leave blank for a non-expiring key.\n\n### Copy It Once — It Is Shown Only Once\n\nWhen you click **Issue Key**, Forge shows the full key **one time**, with a copy button. Forge never stores the key itself, so it can never show you the secret again. Copy it right then into your integration's settings or your password manager. If you lose it, you can't get it back; you revoke the key and issue a new one.\n\n### Keys Cannot Issue Keys\n\nA deliberate guardrail: the user a key signs in as **cannot** issue keys itself. Only a real Admin, working in the app, can create keys. This prevents a leaked integration key from creating more keys and widening its own access.\n\n### The Key List\n\nEach row shows the key's name, the bound user's email, its role-template (if any), an Active/Revoked status chip, last-used and expiry dates. **Last Used** reads *Never* until the key makes its first call — a quick way to spot a key that was issued but never wired up.\n\n### Revoking a Key\n\nTo retire a key, click the **block** icon on its row. Revocation is immediate and permanent — the key stops working on its next call. Revoke a key the moment an integration is decommissioned or you suspect the secret leaked, then issue a fresh one if the integration is still needed.\n\n### Quick Hygiene Rules\n\n- One key per integration, named so you know what it is.\n- Bind to the least-privileged user that still works; use a role template to narrow further.\n- Set an expiry on anything temporary.\n- Revoke unused or compromised keys promptly — the audit trail and the **Last Used** column help you find them.\n- The Connections registry (Admin → Connections) lists every issued key alongside other credentials for a single audit view.","sections":[]}"""
        });

