            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":75,"questionsPerQuiz":4,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"ak1","text":"You issue a new system API key. When can you see the full key value?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Any time, by clicking the key's row to reveal it"},{"id":"b","text":"Only once, right after issuing — Forge never stores the key itself and can never show it again","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"For 24 hours after issuing, then it's hidden"},{"id":"d","text":"It is emailed to the bound user"}],"explanation":"The full key is shown exactly once, immediately after issuing, with a copy button. Forge never keeps the key itself. If you lose the value you must revoke the key and issue a new one."},{"id":"ak2","text":"Every API key must be bound to what?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"A specific IP address"},{"id":"b","text":"A real user — the key authenticates as that person and inherits their permissions","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A company location"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — keys are anonymous"}],"explanation":"Keys are user-bound. The key acts as the chosen user, so pick a least-privileged user that still meets the integration's needs. An optional role template can narrow the key's effective roles further."},{"id":"ak3","text":"Why can't the user that an API key authenticates as issue more API keys?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Because keys expire too quickly to be useful for that"},{"id":"b","text":"It's a privilege-escalation guardrail — only an interactive Admin can mint keys, so a leaked key can't mint more keys","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Because the key-issuing tab is only visible on desktop"},{"id":"d","text":"They can, if the key has an expiry date set"}],"explanation":"Issuing keys is Admin-only and is deliberately kept out of reach of the user a key signs in as. This stops a leaked integration key from creating additional keys and widening its access."},{"id":"ak4","text":"You suspect a system API key's secret has leaked. What should you do?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Rename the key so the old name is no longer valid"},{"id":"b","text":"Click the block (revoke) icon on its row — revocation is immediate; then issue a fresh key if the integration is still needed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Change the bound user's password, which rotates the key"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — keys can't be revoked once issued"}],"explanation":"Revoking a key stops it working on its next call, immediately and permanently. Revoke a compromised or decommissioned key right away, then issue a new one if needed."}]}"""
