            AppRoutes = """["/admin/settings"]""",
            Tags = """["admin","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"The deeper notes an experienced admin reaches for — the edge cases and judgment calls behind reference data, users and teams, integrations, and company settings. Skim it when something behaves in a way the basic screens don't explain.\n\n## Reference Data & Terminology\n\n- **Effective dates.** Each lookup value can carry an optional start and end date. The value is only offered inside that window; outside it, it drops off the menus even though it still exists. Use this for something like a tax-year category that should only show for a while. Marking a value inactive hides it no matter the dates.\n- **Grouping.** All the dropdown lists live in one place, sorted into groups (item kinds, expense categories, lead sources, and so on). A group can sit under another to form a tree, and values keep a set order within their group. A value's short code stays fixed for the life of the value; its label is the text your people actually see.\n- **Where values come from.** The Reference Data tab is **read-only** — you can't add, edit, reorder, or delete here. New or changed lists are set up for your install during onboarding, and the ones that shipped with the app are marked as built-in. Once a change is in, the value shows up here and in the matching menus.\n- **Kiosk and signed-out screens.** These lists also feed the screens people see before they sign in — the shop-floor kiosk and the wall display — so menus and labels are ready without a login. Those screens only show values that are active and inside their date window.\n- **Terminology.** Every label you can rename lives on the Terminology tab; leave one blank and the app shows its built-in wording. Save a rename and everyone sees it right away; clear the custom text to go back to the standard label.\n\n## Users / Roles / Teams\n\n- **Badge reader pairing.** The Users tab can connect a badge reader plugged into that computer; the page shows whether it's connected and offers a helper download so the reader can register scans. Each scan you capture is saved as a badge or tag on that person.\n- **Printable badges.** A person's badge barcode is built from the tag on their account, so you can print it and have them scan it at a kiosk to clock in with badge + PIN.\n- **Deleting a team.** Kiosks and board lanes are tied to a team, so deleting a team asks you to confirm first. Deleting it never removes the people on it — it only removes the team itself and unhooks the kiosks and lanes that pointed at it.\n- **Work Location & state withholding.** The **Work Location** field on the user form only appears once you have more than one location. Whichever location a person is on (or the default, if you leave it blank) decides which **state withholding** forms they're asked to complete.\n\n## Integrations / Connections\n\n- **Switching accounting mode is a planned change.** Moving between Standalone and a connected provider affects the whole install and doesn't take effect instantly — treat a provider switch as scheduled maintenance, not a quick toggle mid-shift.\n- **Some tabs are turned off until enabled.** The Connections registry and the API-key tabs appear only when API keys are switched on for your install; the audit log appears only when audit logging is on. When the matching feature is off, the buttons are greyed out and a banner explains why, and the table stays empty.\n- **Reading the Connections registry.** It's a read-only summary that pulls every credential into one list. Each row's **Owner** is a person's email for a personal credential, or **Install-level** for one that belongs to the whole company. The status chips are color-coded: green means live (Active, Connected, Linked); amber means it needs renewal soon (Expired); grey means it's off (Revoked, Disconnected, Inactive). The list never changes anything — **Manage** takes you to each connection's own page to act on it.\n- **Carrier credentials live on the Carriers page.** Shipping-carrier logins are entered only on the **Carriers** admin page, where each carrier has a Test button to check the connection. The Integrations page may show a carrier card for status, but entering the login and testing it belong on the Carriers page.\n- **Test mode & sandboxes.** An install can be set to a test mode that skips every outside service and returns stand-in responses — handy for setup without live credentials. For each provider, the page shows setup notes and sign-up links to help you get real credentials before you go live.\n\n## Company Settings / Audit / API keys\n\n- **Audit log is permanent.** Audit entries can only be added — no one can edit or delete them. They're kept about 90 days by default (adjustable in system settings), and you can download the log as a spreadsheet to hand to an outside auditor.\n- **The Action filter is flexible.** The audit log's **Action** filter takes both the common choices (Create, Update, Delete, sign-in events) and free text, so you can filter on a familiar action or type in an exact one.\n- **How an API key inherits access.** Every System or BI key is tied to a real person and acts as that person. An optional **Role Template** trims the key down to fewer roles than that person has, so a reporting key can be given only what it needs. The person a key acts as can't issue keys itself — **keys cannot issue keys** — so a leaked key can't create more. The secret is shown **once**, at issue, and never again.\n- **Secrets are never shown back.** Once you save a login or secret for an integration, the settings screen only ever shows that it's set and when it was last used — never the secret itself.\n- **Irreversible stages protect the books.** A stage can be tied to an accounting document (such as Invoice or Payment) and marked irreversible. Once a stage creates an accounting document, marking it irreversible stops jobs from sliding back past it — the accounting document is what justifies the lock, so you set the two up together.","sections":[]}"""
